### User:
why does this command give error Permission denied (publickey):

ssh -i "~/UserKey.pem" -C -L 25900:localhost:5900 ec2-34-221-131-108.us-west-2.compute.amazonaws.com

### Response:


The error "Permission denied (publickey)" indicates that the SSH server on the remote host does not have permission to access your private key file. This can occur if you are using a passwordless authentication method, such as public-key authentication, and do not have sufficient permissions to read or write files in the home directory of the user running the ssh command.

To resolve this issue, make sure that the user running the ssh command has permission to access your private key file by checking its ownership and permissions using the following commands:
```
ls -l ~/.ssh/UserKey.pem
chmod 600 ~/.ssh/UserKey.pem
```
If you do not have write permission for the user running the ssh command, change the ownership of your private key file to that user using the following command:
```
sudo chown -R $USER ~/.ssh
```
Replace `$USER` with the username of the user running the ssh command.
